commit.message:
Assorted small cleanups

* Use ** instead of math.pow.

The math module is imported for only one function, pow. It can be
replaced by the built-in ** operator, since we know one of the operands
is a float, the result will always be a float, so the operator is
equivalent to the function.

* Make code a bit more pythonic.

- Remove unnecessary brackets.
- Use "in" instead of str.find(...) != 1.
- Pass a tuple of prefixes to str.startswith, instead of checking each
  prefix separately.

* Don't check for None.

If the attribute is None, return self.attr is sufficient to return None,
which is what falling off the end of the function will do anyway.

* Fix backslashes in raw strings.

* Simplify re.match.

There is a simpler way to get the matched string from a re search.

However, since all the regexes we use are anchored with ^ and $, the
match can only ever be the entire string anyway, so we should really
just do

matches.append(wpart)

but maybe there's a reason for not doing this that I don't understand.

* Create log dir for tests.

commit.message: Stop installing extra files using data_files

Tweak setup.py to not have \n in description

Newer setuptools enforces that no field except long_description may
contain line breaks. Fix setup.py accordingly.

Switch mainline to Python 3.x only

This has been a long time coming, and Marc Sommerhalder finally pestered
me enough to follow through. Python 3.x is now at the same point the
last version of Python 2.x was at: .7.

This commit doesn't change all that much that wasn't on the Python3
branch already: it updates the README, gets rid of some specical casing
and updates infrastructure.

Oh, and we're now at 1.0. Not that that you should ascribe much meaning
to that, but it's a big enough change to warrant a major bump.

More Python3 work, cleanup and more tests

- Use `future` Python module[0] to make source unified between Py2 and
  Py3. This is a new dependency. It also makes PyMETAR incompatible with
  PyPy and PyPy3 for now, though with a few edits it can be made
  compatible.
- Add a new set of smoke test input files to the tarball
- Make `runtests.sh` run both Py2 and Py3 as test interpreters. If
  someone doesn't have both installed, this will naturally fail, but
  `runtests.sh` is not intended for end-users, so it should be okay.
- autopep8/flake8 all the things.

[0] http://python-future.org/

First stab at converting PyMETAR to Python3

I *may* make an attempt at keeping it compatible with both Py2.7 and
Py3, but whether that will eb supported depends on how much hassle it
is.
Update README and make it Markdown

Fix URLs and shebangs

These days, the default Python interpreter often is Python 3.x, so
change the shebangs to #!/usr/bin/python2.

Also, the original server for the METAR reports has been shut down, so
switch to the new address. Additonally, the site location search page
has disappeared, so subsitute a working one.
Make v0.20, mostly for packaging purposes

Run autopep8 on all Python files

This change should be a functional no-op.

TODO: script this into the git commit process or at least into the
      source tarball creation step.

Fix README, module docstring and regenerate librarydoc.txt

The README is now better ReSt to help with displaying it on PyPI. In a
similar vein, the module-level docstring is now less boilerplate-y
(moved the GPL info and copyright banner to comments). Finally,
regenerate librarydoc.txt to reflect dostring changes.
Make complex long lines more distinct from following block lines
Thanks for fighting me, git and vim
Ignore vim swap files and compiled bytecode everywhere
